{
  "doc_id": "45934",
  "text": "Our understanding of the relationship between gut microbiota and the development of liver disease has been highlighted in both animal and human studies (see Table 1 ). Small intestinal bacterial overgrowth (SIBO), increased intestinal permeability, and a number of bacterial endotoxins were reported as putative factors for NASH development [CITATION_1] . In the first observation, the authors hypothesized an important role for SIBO in the occurrence of NASH, but in recent years, the development of metagenomic sequencing technologies has allowed the description of detailed alterations of the gut microbiota, focusing on qualitative dysbiosis rather than quantitative modifications [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] .",
